node.text: So great getting deep and @honest with amazing mama, Jessica Alba! We chatted about everything from being a mother to 3, attempting to balance work and life, and why started her company after becoming a mother. Jess also shared that she and her oldest daughter go to therapy together, which I love, as a way to keep the lines of communication open and avoid the pitfalls that can arise during the teenage years. She had some great mommy tips: always have an extra set of clothes, always have snacks on hand (especially in the car), and always know it will take more than 15 minutes to leave the house. For even more amazing insights, watch the full interview with Jess, and make sure to tune in next week for another new episode!

node.text: Another great episode of BDA Baby today, with Megan, one half of @feedinglittles, an account that is a must follow for every parent! We broke down some of the myths around solids, some of with were very surprising. Lots of the way we feed our children is just based on “that’s they way it’s been done” rather than on science, and I love how Megan explained everything. She also told us that just because your child doesn’t like it once, don’t give up, eat with your children, and make the same meals. There are so many more tips in here — you might just need to watch! Tune in next week, same time, same place. 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: Let’s talk about sex… after baby! Dr. Cassidy and I had so much fun talking last time, that I had to have her back. This time, we discussed this much requested topic of sex and intimacy after baby, something that is not nearly talked about enough. I love Dr. Cassidy’s advice that it really is all about communication with your partner, and that intimacy doesn’t just have to mean sex. While she doesn’t necessarily recommend scheduling sex, she does recommend making sure you make time for each other and that’s why communication is so important and not building up resentment or feelings of guilt. If you want to hear more from Dr. Cassidy, you can rewatch our first BDA episode (in IGTV) and make sure to listen to @holdingspacepodcast! Tune in next week for another great episode! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: What a beautiful conversation today with the loveliest couple, Matt and Elliott! I learned of their story — Elliot’s sister donated her eggs, and Matt’s 61 year old mother was their gestational carrier — and have been dying to chat with them. Matt and Elliott knew they wouldn’t be able to have kids by traditional means, but never expected that they would be lucky enough to generically both be a part of their daughter, Uma. They also chatted with me about their new life on the road, as the pandemic made them yearn for a life with less things and more adventure! I’m so inspired by Matt and Elliott, and I can’t wait to keep up with their adventures with adorable Uma as they travel! Thanks, guys for joining me, and sharing your amazing, courageous, and beautiful story with me. Tune in next week for another new episode! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: Such a great conversation today with the phenomenal founder and brains beyond @eatcerebelly, Dr, Teresa Purzner! If you’ve been following along, you know I’ve moved on to solids with my daughter, and the struggle is definitely real to feed her a healthy, nutritious, and balanced meal. Teresa was so helpful in explaining what exactly we should be feeding our children for optimal brain development, and what to look for (and look out for) on labels! Look for DHA (not ALA), choline, and zinc — all important in supporting early brain development. Also look for veggies first in the ingredients. This means more nutrition, less sugar. Try to avoid filler foods, such as apples, because they are packed with sugar. Luckily, in designing Cerebelly, Teresa used her background as a neuroscientist and as a mom to make delicious food that kids wants to eat and is healthy and great for neurological development! Head up to my stories for a special discount to try out Cerebelly with your little ones, using code KATHERINE40. Make sure to tune in next week for another episode of BDA Baby with another great guest! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: For the grand finale of Father’s Day week, I was thrilled to be joined by none other than my dad! We chatted all about how his childhood in Austria informed how he parented. Growing up, we had lots of rules, and while I didn’t love them then, now as a parent myself, I have such an appreciation! My dad also talked about what it’s been like watching us kids get older, and watching us step into new roles like parenthood. I also asked him how the transition to being a grandfather ( or Opa) has been, and well, it seems he loves it, especially when we leave and there are no diapers left for him to change ! 😂 I love you, Daddy! Thanks for joining BDA Baby, and especially for teaching me to turn off the lights, make my bed, and to do my laundry! Tune in next Thursday for a normally scheduled episode, and have a happy Father’s Day! 🍼#BDABaby

node.text: Such a hilarious and heartfelt conversation with the amazing Al Roker today (with so much fun commentary from my mom, @mariashriver, and Al’s phenomenal wife, @debrobertsabc). Al shared about his oldest daughter’s wedding a few weeks ago and his other daughter’s college graduation. We also delved into the relationship Al has with his son, Nick, who has special needs, which Al has opened up about in recent years. Al has proudly shared Nick’s participation and wins with @specialolympics, an organization I love, and is near to my heart. It was wonderful hearing from Al about how he parents all three of his kids differently, yet at the end of the day, it’s all really about loving and supporting them. Thank you, Al (and Deborah) for chatting with me, and happy early Father’s Day! Make sure to tune in tomorrow for the grand Father’s Day finale with none other then my father, @schwarzenegger! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: So thrilled to continue Father’s Day week with another amazing dad, John Kanell! John and his husband, @briandow, welcomed their twins, Lachlan and George, via surrogate. John shared their experience, from Brian getting the information on a Facebook group, to meeting the surrogate, Ashley, to their early experience in the NICU. As John shared, the upside to those early days in the NICU where the boys have always been on a schedule, and as any parent knows, getting on a sleep schedule is hard! It was also amazing hearing how John has been able to prioritize both his job and being a parent, AND been able to get the boys involved in cooking with him! John learned to cook from his mother, so he is clearly passing it on, and creating amazing memories for his sons. Thank you for joining me, John, and I hope we can bake together some day soon! Have a great Father’s Day. Make sure to tune in tomorrow for another amazing episode of BDA Baby, with everyone’s favorite weatherman, @alroker! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: Mike Rosenthal and his wife, @jenatkinhair, recently welcomed their son, River, via surrogate, and I was so thrilled to chat with Mike today ahead of his first Father’s Day! Mike explained how he always knew that he and his wife knew they wanted to be parents, but earlier in their marriage they both were building their careers and decided to wait. Luckily, they had planned early on, and froze embryos. Never did they expect to be going through the process of surrogacy during a pandemic, which made the experience very remote and very dependent on FaceTime! I loved what Mike said as we were ending our conversation, that no matter how you have children, you are a family. This could not be more true, and Mike, I am so happy for your wonderful family! node.text: Thank you so much to Beleaf in Fatherhood’s Glen Henry for joining me today to kick off Father’s Day Week! I first saw Glen in my friend @brycedhoward’s amazing film, “Dads” last year. Glen previously was a stay at home dad. As he mentions in the conversation, he first thought staying home would be “easy,” which he quickly learned how far from the truth that was! Using his own experience, he has helped to show the realities of fatherhood and of parenthood, most importantly that presence in your kids life is more important than presents. Thank you for this real and very needed chat, Glen! Make sure to tune in tomorrow at 9am PT with guest @mrmikerosenthal for another special edition Father’s Day BDA Baby! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: I loved chatting with today’s guest, Eva Amurri, for this episode of BDA Baby, which also happened to be one of the most requested topics! Eva and her ex, Kyle, announced they were separating while she was pregnant with her 3rd child, and they divorced just a month before he was born. They have been extremely open and transparent about why they decided to split, yet have also made a commitment to remain in each other’s lives as co-parents. Eva explained that while they are no longer together romantically, they are very much in each other’s lives, and get along much better now. It was great to hear all about how they parent together, work better together now, and how the more open we are about the realities of life, the more it can help others. I truly hope you listen to this eye opening conversation, and thank you Eva for joining me! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: What a great time today chatting with Entrepreneur and mama, Chriselle Lim! Chriselle is mom to two beautiful daughters and is the cofounder of @bumoparent, @bumobrain, @bumowork, and @beingbumo. Bümo began as a way to make parenting easier, especially during the first few years when Chriselle felt like she was either missing out on her daughter’s life or not having enough time to fill up her own cup. She went about creating this remarkable space, only to have COVID put the physical space on hold until last week! During COVID, @bumobrain was born, becoming a virtual teaching platform for children 1-7. I love that Chriselle has created this amazing company that so many parents and children can benefit from. Make sure to check out all that Bümo has to offer — I can’t wait to eventually visit the in person space at the Century City Mall! node.text: So great getting deep and @honest with amazing mama, Jessica Alba! We chatted about everything from being a mother to 3, attempting to balance work and life, and why started her company after becoming a mother. Jess also shared that she and her oldest daughter go to therapy together, which I love, as a way to keep the lines of communication open and avoid the pitfalls that can arise during the teenage years. She had some great mommy tips: always have an extra set of clothes, always have snacks on hand (especially in the car), and always know it will take more than 15 minutes to leave the house. For even more amazing insights, watch the full interview with Jess, and make sure to tune in next week for another new episode!

node.text: Another great episode of BDA Baby today, with Megan, one half of @feedinglittles, an account that is a must follow for every parent! We broke down some of the myths around solids, some of with were very surprising. Lots of the way we feed our children is just based on “that’s they way it’s been done” rather than on science, and I love how Megan explained everything. She also told us that just because your child doesn’t like it once, don’t give up, eat with your children, and make the same meals. There are so many more tips in here — you might just need to watch! Tune in next week, same time, same place. 🍼 #BDABaby

A TRUE FORCE! 🍀 Happy 100th birthday to you Grandma! She changed the world and continues to, even from heaven. She was a daughter, sister, wife, mother, grandmother and creator of @specialolympics I love this video because as her granddaughter, I saw her drive and motivation to make the world better and fiercely fight for those with intellectual disabilities. I also saw her JOY around her family, the playful and beautiful bond she had with my grandpa, the LOVE she had for her 5 kids and the fun she had with us grandchildren. We all remember her with such love and laugh thinking of all the fun memories we have.  I know you’re celebrating in heaven with sugar cookies and angel food cake. We love you and miss you every day. #eks100

node.text: Let’s talk about sex… after baby! Dr. Cassidy and I had so much fun talking last time, that I had to have her back. This time, we discussed this much requested topic of sex and intimacy after baby, something that is not nearly talked about enough. I love Dr. Cassidy’s advice that it really is all about communication with your partner, and that intimacy doesn’t just have to mean sex. While she doesn’t necessarily recommend scheduling sex, she does recommend making sure you make time for each other and that’s why communication is so important and not building up resentment or feelings of guilt. If you want to hear more from Dr. Cassidy, you can rewatch our first BDA episode (in IGTV) and make sure to listen to @holdingspacepodcast! Tune in next week for another great episode! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: What a beautiful conversation today with the loveliest couple, Matt and Elliott! I learned of their story — Elliot’s sister donated her eggs, and Matt’s 61 year old mother was their gestational carrier — and have been dying to chat with them. Matt and Elliott knew they wouldn’t be able to have kids by traditional means, but never expected that they would be lucky enough to generically both be a part of their daughter, Uma. They also chatted with me about their new life on the road, as the pandemic made them yearn for a life with less things and more adventure! I’m so inspired by Matt and Elliott, and I can’t wait to keep up with their adventures with adorable Uma as they travel! Thanks, guys for joining me, and sharing your amazing, courageous, and beautiful story with me. Tune in next week for another new episode! 🍼 #BDABaby

node.text: Such a great conversation today with the phenomenal founder and brains beyond @eatcerebelly, Dr, Teresa Purzner! If you’ve been following along, you know I’ve moved on to solids with my daughter, and the struggle is definitely real to feed her a healthy, nutritious, and balanced meal. Teresa was so helpful in explaining what exactly we should be feeding our children for optimal brain development, and what to look for (and look out for) on labels! Look for DHA (not ALA), choline, and zinc — all important in supporting early brain development. Also look for veggies first in the ingredients. This means more nutrition, less sugar. Try to avoid filler foods, such as apples, because they are packed with sugar. Luckily, in designing Cerebelly, Teresa used her background as a neuroscientist and as a mom to make delicious food that kids wants to eat and is healthy and great for neurological development! Head up to my stories for a special discount to try out Cerebelly with your little ones, using code KATHERINE40. Make sure to tune in next week for another episode of BDA Baby with another great guest! 🍼 #BDABaby
